HEADWORD: Physiography
<hw>Phys`i*og"ra*phy</hw>
<pr>(f⟦icr⟧z`⟦icr⟧*⟦ocr⟧g"r⟦adot⟧*f⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>fy`sis</grk> nature + <ets>-graphy</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>physiographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science which
treats of the earth's exterior physical features, climate, life, etc.,
and of the physical movements or changes on the earth's surface, as the
currents of the atmosphere and ocean, the secular variations in heat,
moisture, magnetism, etc.; physical geography.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The descriptive part of a natural science as
distinguished from the explanatory or theoretic part; <as>as, mineral
<ex>physiography</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Physiolatry</ent>⟦br⟧
